faq:
  - q: "What are the most common interview questions?"
    a: "The most common interview questions fall into five categories: (1) Self-introduction — Tell me about yourself. (2) Motivation — Why do you want this role? Why are you leaving? (3) Behavioral — Tell me about a time you... (4) Situational — What would you do if... (5) Closing — Do you have any questions for us? The behavioral category is where most candidates lose ground — specificity and quantification are what separate strong answers from forgettable ones."
  - q: "How do I answer 'tell me about yourself' in an interview?"
    a: "Use the Present-Past-Future framework. Present: who you are professionally right now and at what level. Past: the most relevant experience that makes you a credible candidate for this role. Future: what you are targeting next and why this role fits. Keep it to 90 seconds. Do not start from the beginning of your career. Do not be modest about your seniority — name it."
  - q: "What is the best answer to 'why do you want to work here'?"
    a: "Name something specific — a product decision, engineering approach, recent announcement, or team mission — that you find genuinely interesting. Then connect it to what you are trying to accomplish in the next phase of your career. The worst answers are generic: 'great culture', 'exciting opportunity', 'I've always admired this company.' These signal zero research. One specific, genuine observation beats five enthusiastic generalities."
  - q: "How do I answer 'what is your greatest weakness'?"
    a: "Choose a genuine weakness that is not disqualifying for this specific role. Describe what you have noticed about yourself, how you manage it, and evidence of improvement. Strong answers show self-awareness and a learning arc — not a rehearsed non-answer like 'I work too hard' or 'I am a perfectionist.'"
  - q: "What questions should I ask at the end of an interview?"
    a: "Ask questions that show you have thought seriously about the role and the team: What does success look like in this role in the first 90 days? What is the biggest challenge the team is facing right now? How do decisions get made on this team? What is the engineering or technical culture like day-to-day? Avoid questions about salary, benefits, or time off in early-stage interviews — they signal misaligned priorities."
  - q: "How should I prepare for an interview in one week?"
    a: "Day 1: Research the company, team, and role deeply. Day 2: Prepare your Tell Me About Yourself answer and write 6 behavioral stories using STAR. Day 3: Review the job description and map your experience to each requirement. Day 4: Prepare 5 thoughtful questions to ask the interviewer. Day 5: Practice all answers out loud — record yourself. Day 6: Do a full mock interview. Day 7: Light review only — rest and sharpen focus."
howto:
  name: "How to Prepare for a Job Interview"
  steps:
    - name: "Research the company and role"
      text: "Read the company's recent press releases, engineering or product blog, and LinkedIn page for the team you are joining. Understand their core product, business model, recent strategic moves, and how this role fits. Interviewers distinguish between candidates who prepared and candidates who read the About page."
    - name: "Prepare your Tell Me About Yourself answer"
      text: "Use Present-Past-Future. Present: your current role and level. Past: the most relevant experience for this interview. Future: what you are targeting and why this role fits. Practice it until it takes 90 seconds and sounds natural."
    - name: "Build 6 behavioral stories using STAR"
      text: "Cover: technical tradeoff, execution under pressure, cross-functional conflict, leadership without authority, failure and recovery, measurable business impact. Each story should have a specific decision, specific outcome, and specific number."
    - name: "Map your experience to the job description"
      text: "Read the job description line by line. For each requirement, identify a specific example from your experience that demonstrates it. This is your evidence base for every question they can ask."
    - name: "Prepare 5 thoughtful questions for the interviewer"
      text: "Ask about: success metrics for the role, current team challenges, decision-making culture, technical stack or process specifics, and what the interviewer values most in candidates they hire. These questions demonstrate seriousness and generate useful information for your own decision."
    - name: "Practice out loud — record yourself"
      text: "Behavioral interviews are verbal. Reading answers silently does not prepare you for speaking them under pressure. Record yourself answering common questions and watch for filler words, rambling, and lack of specificity."
